<div class="description">
    <h3>Description</h3>

    <div class="body">
        <p>The purpose of Zend_Json_Expr is to emit Javascript expressions into a JSON serialized stream, but this purpose conflicts with the JSON standard itself:</p>

<p><a href="http://www.ietf.org/rfc/rfc4627.txt">http://www.ietf.org/rfc/rfc4627.txt</a></p>

<p>Section "2.1 Values" states:</p>

<p>{quote}
 A JSON value MUST be an object, array, number, or string, or one of
   the following three literal names:</p>

<pre><code>  false null true
</code></pre>

<p>{quote}</p>

<p>There is no space in the standard for Javascript expressions.</p>

<p>I suggest moving this class out of the Zend_Json package to remove confusion or the appearance of a non-standard implementation.</p>

<p>Really, this feature is generating Javascript, not JSON, so it should be called Zend_Javascript_Expr, or something similar.</p>

